4 SECTION 2. IC 36-1.5-4.1 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
5 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
6 UPON PASSAGE]:
7 Chapter 4.1. Reorganization of Certain Townships
8 Sec. 1. This chapter does not apply to a township in a county
9 having a consolidated city.
10 Sec. 2. To the extent that other provisions in this article conflict
11 with this chapter, this chapter controls.
12 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "designated unit" means:
13 (1) a county or municipality that is named by a township in a
14 resolution under section 11 of this chapter; or
15 (2) a county to which section 12 or 21 of this chapter applies.
16 Sec. 4. As used in this chapter, "plan" or "plan of
17 reorganization" means a plan of reorganization approved by the
18 legislative body of a designated unit under this chapter.
19 Sec. 5. As used in this chapter, "reorganization" means the
20 dissolution of a township and the transfer of township property,
21 functions, powers, and services to the designated unit.
22 Sec. 6. As used in this chapter, "township" means either of the
23 following:
24 (1) A township that satisfies all of the following criteria:
25 (A) The township has a population of less than six
26 thousand seven hundred (6,700) as determined by the most
27 recent federal decennial census.
28 (B) The township does not operate a fire department.
29 (C) In calendar year 2024, the total value of benefits
30 provided to recipients of township assistance (as reported
31 in the township's annual statistical report under
32 IC 12-20-28-3) was at least two hundred percent (200%) of
33 the sum of all compensation paid to township employees
34 (as reported in the township's annual report filed under
35 IC 5-11-13-1).
36 (2) A township that satisfies all of the following criteria:
37 (A) At least eighty percent (80%) of the township's
38 boundaries coincide with a municipality's boundaries.
39 (B) At least fifty-one percent (51%) of the township's
40 population resides within the corporate boundaries of a
41 municipality described in clause (A).
42 (C) The township does not operate a fire department.
2026 IN 1315—LS 6995/DI 87

3
1 Sec. 7. As used in this chapter, "township office" refers to any
2 of the following:
3 (1) The office of township trustee elected as provided in
4 IC 36-6-4-2.
5 (2) The office of township assessor elected as provided in
6 IC 36-6-5-1 (if the office exists).
7 (3) The office of a member of the township board elected as
8 provided in IC 36-6-6-2.
9 Sec. 8. As used in this chapter, "township services" means the
10 following:
11 (1) Township assistance under IC 12-20 and IC 12-30-4.
12 (2) Provision of insulin to the poor under IC 12-20-16.
13 (3) Fire protection services under IC 36-8.
14 (4) Fence viewing under IC 32-26.
15 (5) Provision and maintenance of cemeteries under IC 23-14.
16 (6) Provision and maintenance of township parks and
17 community centers under IC 36-10.
18 (7) Destruction of detrimental plants, noxious weeds, and rank
19 vegetation under IC 15-16-8.
20 (8) Any other services required by statute to be provided by
21 a township.
22 Sec. 9. (a) On January 1, 2028, each township is dissolved. All of
23 the following occur:
24 (1) The term of office of an individual who holds a township
25 office ends on December 31, 2027. An election for a township
26 office shall not be held in 2028 or thereafter.
27 (2) The:
28 (A) powers and duties of the office of township trustee are
29 transferred to the executive of the designated unit;
30 (B) legislative powers and duties of the office of township
31 board members are transferred to the legislative body of
32 the designated unit;
33 (C) fiscal powers and duties of the office of township board
34 members are transferred to the fiscal body of the
35 designated unit; and
36 (D) powers and duties of the township assessor (if the office
37 exists) are transferred to the county assessor.
38 (3) The boundaries of the dissolved township remain as the
39 boundaries of the service area within which the designated
40 unit provides township services.
41 (4) The balance in the general fund of the township shall be
42 transferred to the general fund of the designated unit.
2026 IN 1315—LS 6995/DI 87

4
1 (5) The balance in the township assistance fund of a township
2 shall be transferred to a township assistance fund established
3 by the designated unit.
4 (6) The balance of any other fund of the township shall be
5 transferred to the fund of the designated unit that most
6 closely corresponds to the fund of the township.
7 (7) Subject to section 26 of this chapter, the property and
8 liabilities of the township become the property and liabilities
9 of the designated unit.
10 (b) IC 36-1-8-5 does not apply to a balance referred to in
11 subsection (a).
12 Sec. 10. (a) A township that is described in:
13 (1) section 6(1) of this chapter and that is adjacent to a
14 municipality; or
15 (2) section 6(2) of this chapter;
16 may designate the municipality in a resolution under section 11 of
17 this chapter. A township is not adjacent to a municipality if the
18 township and municipality are connected by a strip of land that is
19 less than one hundred fifty (150) feet wide.
20 (b) A township that is described in section 6(1) or 6(2) of this
21 chapter may designate a county in a resolution under section 11 of
22 this chapter.
23 Sec. 11. (a) The legislative body of a township shall adopt a
24 resolution not later than June 1, 2026, that:
25 (1) proposes a reorganization; and
26 (2) designates:
27 (A) one (1) municipality; or
28 (B) one (1) county;
29 that satisfies the criteria under section 10 of this chapter for
30 reorganizing with the township.
31 (b) The township trustee of the township shall certify the
32 resolution to:
33 (1) the county clerk; and
34 (2) if the designated unit is a municipality, the clerk of the
35 municipality.
36 If the designated unit meets the criteria under section 10 of this
37 chapter, the designated unit and the township shall appoint a joint
38 board under section 14 of this chapter.
39 Sec. 12. If a township fails to adopt a resolution under section 11
40 of this chapter not later than June 1, 2026, the county in which the
41 township is primarily located shall be the designated unit of the
42 township without the township adopting a resolution or taking
2026 IN 1315—LS 6995/DI 87

5
1 further action. A joint board shall be appointed under section 14
2 of this chapter, and the county shall reorganize with the township
3 as provided in this chapter.
4 Sec. 13. If a designated unit is named by two (2) or more
5 townships in resolutions under section 11 of this chapter, the
6 designated unit may:
7 (1) appoint a single joint board under section 14 of this
8 chapter; and
9 (2) prepare and adopt a single reorganization plan;
10 to govern the reorganization of the townships, instead of
11 appointing separate boards and adopting separate plans for each
12 of the townships.
13 Sec. 14. (a) A joint board shall consist of the following:
14 (1) Two (2) members of the township board of each township
15 participating in the reorganization, selected by the members
16 of the township board.
17 (2) Four (4) members of the legislative body of the designated
18 municipality or of the fiscal body of the designated county,
19 whichever is applicable, selected by the members of the body.
20 (3) The township trustee of the township, the fiscal officer of
21 the designated municipality or county, and other members of
22 the bodies under subdivisions (1) and (2) shall serve as
23 advisory, nonvoting members.
24 (b) Four (4) voting members constitute a quorum. Official
25 action may only be taken by affirmative vote of at least a majority
26 of members present at the meeting.
27 (c) The members of a joint board serve without compensation.
28 The members are entitled to reimbursement from the reorganizing
29 township and designated units for the necessary expenses incurred
30 in the performance of their duties.
31 (d) A joint board is subject to IC 5-14-1.5 and IC 5-14-3.
32 (e) The joint board shall prepare a reorganization plan not later
33 than December 1, 2026, for transferring the powers, duties, and
34 property of the township consistent with this chapter. The joint
35 board shall send the plan to the legislative body of the designated
36 unit for adoption.
37 (f) The legislative body of the designated unit may adopt the
38 plan as drafted or modify the plan before adoption.
39 Sec. 15. Elimination of a township office does not invalidate:
40 (1) any resolutions, fees, schedules, or other actions adopted
41 or taken by the township trustee or township assessor (if the
42 office exists) before January 1, 2028; or
2026 IN 1315—LS 6995/DI 87

6
1 (2) any appointments made by the township trustee or
2 township assessor (if the office exists) before January 1, 2028.
3 Sec. 16. In 2027, the fiscal body of the designated unit shall, in
4 the manner provided by IC 6-1.1-17, adopt a budget, tax levies, and
5 tax rates that are sufficient for the designated unit to provide
6 township services within the boundaries of the dissolved township.
7 Sec. 17. (a) The plan of reorganization governs the actions,
8 duties, and powers of the designated unit and the township that are
9 not specified by law.
10 (b) The plan of reorganization must be consistent with this
11 chapter and include at least the following:
12 (1) A description of the township services provided by the
13 designated unit and the service areas in which the services will
14 be offered.
15 (2) The disposition of the personnel, the agreements, the
16 assets, and, subject to section 26 of this chapter, the liabilities
17 of the township, including the terms and conditions upon
18 which the transfer of property and personnel will be achieved.
19 (3) Any other matter that the joint board determines to be
20 necessary or appropriate or to include in the plan of
21 reorganization.
22 (c) When the plan of reorganization is submitted to the
23 designated unit by the joint board, the designated unit shall post a
24 copy of the plan of reorganization on the website of the designated
25 unit not more than seven (7) days after receiving the plan of
26 reorganization from the joint board. If the plan of reorganization
27 is amended, the designated unit shall post the amended plan on the
28 website of the designated unit not later than seven (7) days after
29 the amended plan is adopted.
30 Sec. 18. The legislative body of the designated unit shall certify
31 the legislative body's final action on a plan of reorganization or
32 revised plan of reorganization, as modified by the legislative body,
33 in the manner prescribed by the department of local government
34 finance, to each of the following:
35 (1) The clerk of the circuit court and, if the designated unit is
36 a municipality, the clerk of the municipality.
37 (2) The county fiscal officer of each county in which the
38 township is located.
39 (3) The county recorder of each county in which the township
40 is located.
41 (4) The county voter registration office of each county in
42 which the township is located.
